<<casenuove.functions,echo=F>>=
#' Create a Marriage Network Graph
#'
#' This function creates an undirected graph from marriage data within a specified time window
#' before a given election year.
#'
#' @param marriage_data A data frame containing marriage records with columns:
#'   - year: The year of the marriage
#'   - husband_familyname_std: Standardized husband's family name
#'   - wife_familyname_std: Standardized wife's family name
#' @param election_year The target election year
#' @param years_before Number of years before the election to include (default: 20)
#'
#' @return An igraph graph object representing the marriage network
#' @importFrom igraph graph_from_data_frame
#' @importFrom dplyr filter
#' @export
create_marriage_network <- function(marriage_data, election_year, years_before = 20) {
  marriages_window <- marriage_data %>%
    filter(year <= election_year & year >= election_year - years_before)

  marriage_network <- graph_from_data_frame(
    marriages_window,
    directed = FALSE,
    vertices = unique(c(marriages_window$husband_familyname_std,
                       marriages_window$wife_familyname_std))
  )

  return(marriage_network)
}
@

According to the traditional myth, the Republic of Venice was ruled by a selfless and harmonious patrician elite committed to the common good \citep{gaeta1961alcune,gilbert1968venetian, muir1981civic}. %Muir Ch. 1
Historical reality, however, fell short of this idealized image: political rivalries recurred throughout the Republic's history  \citep{grubb1986myths,cracco1979,queller86}.

For the late medieval and early modern period, scholars have identified a division within the patriciate between a small group of leading families, which controlled  a disproportionate share of major offices, and a broader body of lesser families; the dominant group comprised around forty \emph{casate}, twenty-four belonging to the  \emph{longhi} (long) or \emph{case vecchie} (old houses), that is, families of the most ancient standing, while the remaining were the \emph{grandi curti}, the leading families within the much larger group of \emph{curti} (short) or \emph{case nuove} (new houses). In the second half of the fourteenth century, these forty families accounted for  only 22 per cent of the  181 noble lineages \citep{chojnacki1973search}. Although their larger size gave them more seats and votes in the Great Council, the Republic's main political assembly, than their numerical importance among noble lineages would suggest, they nevertheless remained a minority.\footnote{According to one estimate, the \emph{case vecchie} held about one third of the votes in the Great Council at the beginning of the sixteenth century \citep[p. 93]{finlay1980politicsrenaissance}.} An interesting question, therefore, is how such a small minority came to dominate political office, and what role was played by the remaining families \citep[p. 21-22]{burke1974}. %22% da Cojniacki1973, pag. 51, un terzo (35%) da Finlay pag. 93


 A second striking feature of Venice's political history is that, between 1382 and 1612, every doge --nineteen in total-- came from \emph{grandi curti} families \citep{damosto1966dogi}. This exclusion of the \emph{longhi} was specific to this period and confined to the dogate; the \emph{longhi} continued to hold other prominent positions within the Republic’s major institutions. A further question concerns the reasons underlying this exclusion. Some historical accounts refer to a conspiracy among the \emph{grandi curti} families as a possible explanation; however, the evidence remains inconclusive (\citealp[p.~93]{finlay1980politicsrenaissance};
 \citealp[p.~79]{chojnacki1973search};
 \citealp[p.~421]{romanin1855v4}).

Addressing these two questions requires consideration of the Venetian institutional framework. The Republic comprised over one hundred principal magistracies, including the dogate, most of which were filled through elections held in the Great Council, the plenary  political assembly composed of all members of the patriciate. The council's electoral procedures combined sortition and successive rounds of voting, which often required qualified majorities of over sixty percent. These  high majorities requirements, together with the frequency of elections, fostered the formation of coalitions among noble families, %Finlay p. 3
yet the nature of these coalitions has remained largely unexplored due to the scarcity of direct evidence: the Venetian Republic regarded factional division as a threat to its stability and systematically discouraged open expressions of conflict, leaving little explicit trace of political alignments \citep{van2018people}.

In the absence of direct evidence on political alliances within the Venetian patriciate, this paper reconstruct patterns of cohesion and division  through an analysis of the network of marriages linking noble families, originally assembled by \cite{PugaTrefler}. This approach rests on the premise that, in Venice, marriage was far more than  a private arrangement: it served as a political instrument through which patrician houses forged durable alliances, consolidated electoral support, and secured access to public office. Marriage ties therefore provide a window onto the underlying structure of political relationships. We use this network to investigate whether political alignments were structured along lines of ancestry (i.e. \emph{longhi} versus \emph{curti}), elite membership (i.e. the forty families versus the remaining families), or other, as yet unidentified, forms of political division, and how these patterns evolved over time \dots CONTINUARE QUANDO SARANNO PIU' CHIARI I RISULTATI


We can formulate the following research questions:\begin{itemize}
% We need to adapt all this
\item {\bf Research Question 1} Is there evidence of factions in the social network in the period under consideration? If there is, are {\em longhi} and {\em curti} families in different communities or clearly separated?
\item {\bf Research Question 2} Regardless of the factional divisions, what position did the doge’s family occupy within the social network at the time of election, and what does this reveal about the social status of families that produced a doge?
\item {\bf Research Question 3} Is there any specific social status associated with the sixteen \emph{grandi curti} families that allegedly conspired to exclude the {\em longhi} form the dogate from 1382 and 1612?
\end{itemize}

Addressing these questions would clarify some previously unexplored aspects of the structure of political competition and elite interaction within the Venetian patriciate.

QUI INSERIRE RELATED LITERATURE

%The structure and dynamics of the Venetian patriciate have long been the subject of scholarly debate.

\section{Historical and Institutional Background}\label{history}

Before turning to the analysis of the marriage network, it is necessary to understand the social structure of the Venetian patriciate and the institutional framework within which it operated. Section~3.1 examines the origins of the nobility and the emergence of the distinction between \emph{curti} and \emph{longhi} while Section~3.2 describes the main features of the Venetian electoral system. Together they provide the background needed to interpret the patterns identified in the sections that follow.

\subsection{Political divisions in the Renaissance Venetian patriciate}\label{patriciate}

The Venetian nobility was formally established with the Serrata (closure) of 1297, a measure that restricted access to the Great Council, the main political assembly. This law granted membership to all individuals who had served on the Great Council during the previous four years and to others who had taken part in the government over the preceding thirty years, provided they received a council’s approval. In 1323, a subsequent law made this status hereditary: all male sons of members of the Great Council were automatically admitted upon reaching the age of twenty-five \citep{chojnacki1973search,serrata}.
Despite its name, the Serrata did not lead to a reduction in the size of the Great Council. On the contrary, the number of councillors increased from an average of less than three hundred before the Serrata, to more than one thousand \citep{chojnacki97, raines2003cooptazione}. Beyond its numerical expansion, the closure fundamentally transformed the nature of the institution. Rather than a relatively small body of members elected for limited terms from among the leading families, the Great Council became the permanent plenary assembly of the hereditary patriciate, with membership determined by birth rather than election.

Although  additions to the ranks of the nobility continued  for some times after 1297, hereditary membership was progressively reinforced through a series of subsequent measures. What \citet{second:serrata} has termed the ``second Serrata'' introduced the compulsory registration of patrician births and increasingly rigorous procedures for admission to the Great Council, while the ``third Serrata'' \citep{chojnacki00} required the registration of patrician marriages and tightened the rules governing the hereditary transmission of noble status. Together, these measures made entry into the patriciate progressively more difficult and reinforced its character as a closed hereditary elite.
From the mid-fourteenth century onward, new admissions remained rare until the mid-seventeenth century. The only significant exception was the aggregation of approximately thirty families in 1381, granted in recognition of their financial and military support during the War of Chioggia \citep{raines2003cooptazione}.\footnote{\ New and more substantial waves of admissions occurred in the seventeenth and early eighteenth centuries, when the Republic, faced with the fiscal pressures of prolonged warfare during the War of Candia and the Morean War, opened access to the patriciate in exchange for considerable financial contributions \citep{raines2003cooptazione}.}

The Serrata did not give rise to major episodes of social unrest or sustained protest among those excluded. Social conflict in Venice remained limited, in part because the patriciate preserved stability by ensuring justice and an adequate food supply for the lower classes \citep{pullan1971rich}.
By contrast, tensions were more pronounced within the patriciate itself.
Although the Serrata instituted formal equality under the principle of one man, one vote, the Great Council was nonetheless marked by significant internal divisions. In this context, leading families sought alternative means of asserting pre-eminence and differentiating themselves from their peers.
In the mid-fourteenth century, two lists---one anonymous and the other attributed to the patrician Pietro Giustinian---identified  certain families as  the founders of Venice,  conventionally tracing their origins to the ninth century \citep[p. 398]{raines2006invention1}. Although the lists underwent several revisions and varied in their earliest versions, by the fifteenth century their composition had stabilized at twenty-four families \citep[p.~434]{raines2006invention1} whose names are listed in the second  column of Table~\ref{tab:casenuove.table.parties}.
When the admissions of new nobles after the War of Chioggia reconfigure the balance of power within the patriciate, these twenty-four families came to constitute a distinct political grouping,  increasingly referred to as the \emph{case vecchie} or \emph{longhi}. They stood in opposition to the remaining families, identified as the \emph{case nuove} or \emph{curti}.
Among the \emph{case nuove}, those admitted  after the war were known as the \emph{case nuovissime}, or ``newest houses'' (\citealp{chojnacki1973search}; \citealp[p. 92-96]{finlay1980politicsrenaissance}; \citealp[p. 780]{raines2006invention2}). %(Chojnacki Search, pp. 49-50)


It is important to emphasize that, beyond the conventional narrative, the distinction between \emph{longhi} and \emph{curti} cannot be explained solely by lineage antiquity or wealth. Although the \emph{longhi} generally represented the oldest patrician lineages, several \emph{curti} could also trace their origins back to the early centuries of Venice and enjoyed comparable social prestige. Likewise, economic wealth did not map neatly onto this distinction: some \emph{curti} accumulated great fortunes through trade, while certain \emph{longhi} lineages—or branches within them—experienced significant economic decline.\footnote{At the end of the fifteenth century, the nobleman Priuli noted in his diaries that roughly three quarters of the patriciate were ``poor,'' meaning that they depended on paid public office for their subsistence \citep[p. 73]{finlay1980politicsrenaissance}.} Rather, the distinction reflected the balance of power at the time the lists were compiled, shaped by a combination of genealogical seniority, economic resources, and, more broadly, social and political prestige. In particular, among the \emph{curti}, a group of sixteen families came to be widely recognized as belonging to the political elite. Throughout this paper, we use the term \emph{grandi curti} for these sixteen families, to distinguish them from the remaining \emph{curti}. The second column of Table~\ref{tab:casenuove.table.parties} lists the \emph{grandi curti}. Together with the twenty-four \emph{longhi}, they constituted the so-called "Forty Families", recognized by contemporaries as the dominant political elite of the Venetian Republic throughout the period considered in this study.


<<casenuove.table.parties, message=F, echo=F>>=
sort_with_empty_last <- function(x) {
  x[order(x == "", x)]
}

family_labels <- read.csv("data/family-labels-accession.csv", stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

family_labels[family_labels$Group== "Lunghi",]$Group <- "Longhi"
longhi <- family_labels[ family_labels$Group == "Longhi", ]$Family
ducali <- family_labels[ family_labels$Ducale == 1,]$Family
quaranta_famiglie <- c(longhi,ducali)

quaranta_famiglie <- quaranta_famiglie[ !(quaranta_famiglie %in% c("Steno", "Da Ponte", "Cicogna")) ]

grandi_curti <- ducali[ !(ducali %in% c("Steno", "Ponte", "Cicogna")) ]

max_length <- length(longhi)

length(grandi_curti) <- max_length
grandi_curti[ is.na( grandi_curti )] <- ""

length( ducali ) <- max_length
ducali[ is.na( ducali )] <- ""

family_lists <- data.frame( longhi = sort_with_empty_last(longhi),
                            grandi_curti = sort_with_empty_last(grandi_curti),
                            ducali = sort_with_empty_last(ducali) )

library(kableExtra)
kable(family_lists,
      col.names=c("Longhi","Grandi Curti","Ducali (1382-1612)"),
      caption="Classification of Venetian patrician families") %>%
  row_spec(0,bold=TRUE) %>%
  kable_styling(font_size = 7)
@


\subsection{Electoral institutions and political dynamics}

Following the Serrata, the hereditary nobility described above constituted the membership of the Great Council, the Republic's principal political assembly. and the body responsible for electing the holders of most major offices. Understanding its electoral procedures is therefore essential for interpreting the political significance of the divisions discussed in the previous section.

The Great Council elected the holders of most major offices of the Republic, including the Doge, the six Ducal Councillors, collectively known as the Minor Council, the Senate, the Council of Ten, and the Council of Forty \citep[ch. 1]{maraniniv2}. Including the numerous lower-ranking magistracies, the offices to be filled numbered in the hundreds, and most were held for short terms. As a result, the Great Council met regularly to fill them through elections. These procedures were characterized by three defining features: the frequent use of committees of electors, the selection of their members by lot (sortition), and successive rounds of balloting. By concentrating the final decision in the hands of a relatively small body of electors, these committees facilitated bargaining and compromise among the leading families.

These mechanisms reached their most elaborate form in the election of the Doge, which consisted of ten successive rounds and the formation of five different electoral committees, each requiring large supermajorities. In the final ballot, twenty-five out of forty-one votes were required, a majority of just over sixty per cent  \citep{tucci2014,molinari2020republic}. Such a demanding procedure, together with the Venetian ideal of public office as a service to the common good, exercised by experienced officeholders and constrained to prevent the concentration of personal or family power, shaped the profile of serious contenders. Those elected were typically of advanced age\footnote{\ Given that the office was held for life, candidates considered too young were generally excluded \citep{smith2021long}. Having too many sons could also prove a disadvantage, for fear of nepotism \citep[134]{finlay1980politicsrenaissance}.}  and had a distinguished record of prior office-holding \citep[124–141]{finlay1980politicsrenaissance}. Service in high-ranking posts--—such as ambassadorships--—and a university education were also valued. Because both required substantial financial resources, wealth effectively shaped access to office (\citealp[p. 18--26]{burke1974}; \citealp[p. 28--29]{davis1962}). % per eccezioni Raines invenzioni  p.287-288 Alcune eccezioni di doge che non venivano da famiglie grandi, ricche o prestigiose: Nicolò da Ponte (1578) e Francesco Erizzo (1631). Da ponte: il suo arrivo al dogato frutto di circostanze uniche create dalla lotta per il potere fra famiglie ducali e famiglie del patriziato anziano.
These qualifications, however, were only prerequisites for consideration. As they were often shared by several nobles, competition rarely turned on credentials alone; what ultimately determined success was the breadth of the support a candidate could mobilize within the Great Council.

Precisely because victory depended on assembling such broad coalitions,  ducal elections became a crucial arena of political competition. Renaissance chronicles depict this rivalry as culminating in a conspiracy by sixteen \emph{curti} families which led to the exclusion of the \emph{longhi} from the dogeship between 1382 and 1612, after a prolonged period in which they held it almost continuously  (\citealp[p.~93]{finlay1980politicsrenaissance};
\citealp[p.~79]{chojnacki1973search};
\citealp[p.~421]{romanin1855v4}). %Chojniacki pag. 79 note 18 e 19, romanin nota 2.
 A list of the families that held the office of doge during the conspiracy---the so-called \emph{ducali} families---is provided in the third column of Table~\ref{tab:casenuove.table.parties}.

The extent to which this \emph{longhi–curti} opposition amounted to a genuine and sustained political conflict, however, remains uncertain. As Finlay has observed,
although the \emph{longhi} were excluded from the dogeship during this period, their representation in other major offices was broadly proportional to their numerical strength in the Great Council \citep[92-93]{finlay1980politicsrenaissance}. %anche rainesinventiona pag 443 la mette in dubbio
This suggests that their political marginalisation may have been more limited than the traditional narrative implies.

The chronology of the rivalry is equally problematic. A seventeenth-century account dates the alleged pact among the \emph{curti} families to 1450; however, the exclusion itself began much earlier, and periods of especially intense competition were concentrated in particular elections, most notably those of 1486 and 1521 \citep[145--154]{finlay1980politicsrenaissance}. %Alvise da Mosto, by contrast, traces the pact back to 1414 \cite[p. XLII]{@bookdamosto1966dogi}.
In the election of 1486, which followed the brief nine-month dogeship of Marco Barbarigo, Bernardo Giustinian of the  \emph{longhi} came close to defeating Agostino Barbarigo. Having twice secured twenty-three votes, two short of the required majority, he eventually withdrew in Barbarigo’s favour, reportedly to preserve patrician unity. The \emph{curti} responded by withholding support from \emph{longhi} candidates in the subsequent  yearly elections to the Senate and the Council of Ten (\citealp[p.145--7]{finlay1980politicsrenaissance}; \citealp[p. 439--40]{raines2006invention1}). %anche Raines pag. 49
A similar attempt occurred in  1521, when Giorgio Corner sought to break the \emph{curti}'s hold on the dogeship. Despite his wealth and initially favourable sortition---as several electors were drawn from very small houses not aligned with either candidate---he never secured more than fifteen votes, and Antonio Grimani prevailed. As in the 1486 elections, retaliation against the \emph{longhi} followed and an elector who had backed the \emph{curti} in the final college was rewarded with a procuratorship \citep[p. 152--5]{finlay1980politicsrenaissance}.% ci sarebbe anche 1578 Da ponte. Famiglia nobile alla serrata poi cancellata e poi reinserita nel 1406 (negroponte). Molto dotto. Eletto con 27 voti, dopo con 45 scrutini contro Tiepolo e Soranzo (lungi) e Gritti (curti). Da Mosto p. 370 Vedi anche Raines invention 287-88.

One possible interpretation of this so-called conspiracy, which has not yet been systematically explored, is that it reflected not a rigid division between \emph{longhi} and \emph{curti}, but rather a struggle for dominance among the forty most powerful clans of the city, with many smaller \emph{curti} families at least tacitly aligned with the conspiring ones \citep[p.~94]{finlay1980politicsrenaissance}. Yet, reconstructing political divisions remains difficult. The  Republic of Venice consistently portrayed factional conflict as a danger to its  stability and sought to suppress its overt expression; as a result, traces of organised political groupings in the sources are fragmentary \citep{van2018people}.

This paper, therefore, examines indirect evidence of political alliances using a sequence of  networks  constructed over successive time windows from a dataset of marriages among Venetian noble families compiled by  \cite{PugaTrefler}. In Renaissance Venice, marriage was a central instrument of family strategy and one of the principal mechanisms through which durable political coalitions were forged and maintained.\footnote{\emph{Broglio} likewise helped  to build clienteles, especially in the later period  of the Republic, when impoverished nobles---known as \emph{Sguizeri} (Swiss), in reference  to the mercenary soldiers---were effectively paid  in return for their  votes,
%anche a pagina 20dice dopo Agnadello,
a practice that the Republic consistently sought to curb. In Venice even \emph{broglio onesto}, i.e. the open solicitation of electoral support, was officially forbidden (\citealp[p. 204-218]{finlay1980politicsrenaissance}; \citealp[ch. 3]{queller86}).} It could benefit all families involved: those of lower standing enhanced their status through advantageous matches, while more prestigious lineages secured substantial dowries and strengthened their economic and political networks, as in-laws  became potential business partners and political allies \citep[p.81-82]{dowries:chojnacki, raines2013rameau, finlay1980politicsrenaissance}. %Raines a pag.30
Marriage thus played a crucial role in the political and social management of the family and, for this very reason, offers valuable insight into patterns of cohesion and division within the patriciate.

