\section{Methodology}

<<casenuove.setup, echo=F,message=F>>=
library(dplyr)
library(igraph)

load("data/venice-marriages-filtered.rda")
load("data/ducali_dogi_data.rda")

@

This section in organized as follows. In Section~\ref{ssec:sources}, we describe the different data sources and the preprocessing steps used to harmonize them. In Section~\ref{ssec:validation}, we discuss how these sources were validated, including a description of potential biases. Finally, in Section~\ref{ssec:exploration}  a descriptive and exploratory analysis is introduced.

\subsection{Data sources}\label{ssec:sources}

We rely on three datasets: an existing database of marriages among Venetian nobles, a database of doges elected after 1297, and a third dataset that includes additional information on noble families drawn from secondary sources.

%
<<casenuove.marriages,echo=F,message=F>>=
noble_marriages <- read.csv("data/noble-marriages-year.csv", stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
first_year <- min(noble_marriages$year)
last_year <- max(noble_marriages$year)
@
%
The first dataset, which forms the basis of our network analysis, consists of  Venetian matrimonial records spanning the period from \Sexpr{first_year} to \Sexpr{last_year}. Originally compiled by \cite{PugaTrefler}, it was normalized and adapted by \cite{merelo2024intra} and \cite{histories4020012}. Each record corresponds to a single marriage entry in the Avogaria del Comun registers, the magistracy responsible for recording marriages involving at least one noble. Most entries are dated and include the spouses’ first names and noble family affiliation.

<<casenuove.dogi,echo=F,message=F>>=
load("data/ducali_dogi_data.rda")
ducali_dogi_data <- ducali_dogi_data %>% filter( Year <= 1630)
@

The second dataset provides the names of the doges and the year of their appointment and is taken from the {\sf dogesr} package \citep{merelo2022good} which used the Wikipedia timeline as a source. % Loaded now in the casenuove.table.parties chunk

A third dataset records, for each noble family, its factional affiliation  and the date of its admission to the nobility.  Families are assigned to one of three groups: \emph{longhi}, \emph{grandi curti}, or other \emph{curti}, following  the fifteenth-century classification described in Section~\ref{patriciate}. Admission dates are drawn from \cite{raines2003cooptazione}, which also reports the extinction date for each noble family, defined as the last year in which the family appears in the documentary record. This third dataset is publicly available in the paper repository under an open licence.

Because the three datasets come from different sources, we harmonize family names to ensure consistent identification across records. When a direct match is not possible, we proceed as follows:\begin{itemize}
\item When differences reflect only orthographic variation (e.g., Da Mosto vs Mosto or Mosto, Da), we standardize names to the form used in the Puga and Trefler dataset;

\item When family names in the Puga and Trefler dataset do not exactly match those reported by Raines, we rely on the alternative variants provided by Raines to establish correspondence. For example, the Colleoni/Colleone family appears under Codeglione in Raines, with Colleoni/Colleone listed as variants;

\item When Raines distinguishes between branches of the same family, e.g., Mora (S. Marcuola) and Mora (S. Felice), we collapse them into a single family and assign the earliest admission date, since the matrimonial dataset records only family names rather than individual branches. This applies only to few families, all admitted after the period under study, and therefore does not affect the results.
\end{itemize}

We then exclude observations  that meet any of the following criteria:\begin{itemize}
\item one of the spouses is not noble (identified in the  Puga and Trefler dataset by an empty “Standard Family Name” field);
\item the marriage predates the admission to the nobility of one of the families involved;
\item the marriage is undated.\end{itemize}
The first criterion excludes marriages involving families that never belonged to the patriciate, while the second excludes marriages contracted before a family's admission to the nobility. In both cases, the union cannot represent a political alliance within the patriciate. Undated marriages are excluded because it is not possible to determine the noble status of the spouses at the time of the marriage.  % The file loaded above is already filtered with all these families dropped.


<<casenuove.number_of_marriages_per_year, messages=F,echo=F, fig.cap="Number of marriages per year, 1400--1650.", fig.height=4>>=
library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)
FIRST_YEAR_UNDER_STUDY <- 1400
LAST_YEAR_UNDER_STUDY <- 1650

noble_marriages %>% group_by( year ) %>% summarise( matrimonies=n()) %>% filter( year >= FIRST_YEAR_UNDER_STUDY & year <= LAST_YEAR_UNDER_STUDY ) -> marriages_by_year
ggplot(marriages_by_year, aes(x=year,y=matrimonies))+geom_line()+geom_point()+theme_minimal()+labs(y="Marriages")
@

Restricting the data to the period considered in this study (1400--1650) yields a final dataset of \Sexpr{sum(marriages_by_year$matrimonies)} marriages. Figure~\ref{fig:casenuove.number_of_marriages_per_year} reports the annual number of marriages over this period.


\subsection{Validation and biases}\label{ssec:validation}

The approach adopted in this paper---using marriage networks to reconstruct patterns of political alignment within the Venetian patriciate between 1400 and 1650---rests on two assumptions: that the patrilineal family (\emph{casata}) was the relevant political unit, and that marriage ties reflected political alignment between families.

Despite the growing economic autonomy of the numerous branches into which Venetian patrician families were often divided, the  \emph{casata} remained the primary political unit throughout the period under study. %p. 128 e 141 ma anche pag. 22-24 di cooptazione
 (\citealp[]{raines2013rameau}; \citealp[p. 81-87]{finlay1980politicsrenaissance}; \citealp[]{chojnacki:1985};  \citealp[ch. 3]{romano1987patricians}).\footnote{\ It was only during the eighteenth century that the \emph{casata} lost its political primacy  to its branches \citep{raines2003cooptazione}.} %pag. 50
Branches frequently lived in separate households, yet Republican institutions continued to treat the lineage as the relevant political actor: in many electoral procedures, the selection of one member automatically excluded all the others, effectively making officeholders representatives of their patrician family rather than autonomous political actors \citep[p. 110-111]{maraniniv2}.

Marriage alliances, in turn, had both economic and political significance. As shown by \cite{PugaTrefler}, marriages in the fifteenth century were closely connected to the financing of long-distance trade, while dowries facilitated the transfer of  resources across lineages and helped families maintain or improve their economic and social position \citep{dowries:chojnacki}.
Beyond their economic and commercial functions, marriages also had clear political implications. In-laws formed part of the political network on which a family could rely for political support and  votes in the Great Council. Marriages within different branches of the same lineage could also strengthen family cohesion and lineage consciousness  (\citealp[]{chojnacki:1985}; \citealp[p.~81-96]{finlay1980politicsrenaissance}; \citealp[]{raines2003cooptazione}; \citealp[]{raines2013rameau}; \citealp[ch.~3] {romano1987patricians}). %raines cooptazione pag 24-25
These considerations justify treating the family as the relevant unit of political analysis and marriage ties as meaningful indicators of political alignment.

A separate question concerns the representativeness of the network used in this study. The data assembled by Puga and Trefler  derive from a nineteenth-century manuscript held at the Venice Archivio di Stato and are  largely based on  records of the Avogaria di Comun, which registered  marriages involving noble husbands from the early fifteenth century onward. Following legislation enacted in 1376 and 1422 as part of the process often referred to as the "second Serrata" \citep{second:serrata}, which excluded illegitimate children and those born to socially unworthy mothers of non-noble birth, marriage registration by the Avogaria di Comun became essential for determining eligibility for noble status. This institutional role provides strong reason to believe that the records were systematically maintained, with the exception of the earliest decades of the fifteenth century, when the relatively small number of recorded marriages suggests incomplete coverage. Results for this initial period should therefore be interpreted with caution. Moreover, the quality and completeness of the dataset have already been established in previous work by Puga and Trefler.

<<casenuove.marriages.validation, echo=F,message=F, warning=F, fig.cap="Showing the main events in the Republic of Venice over the smoothed chart of marriages per year. Red: Black Plague of 1479; gold: War of the League of Cambrai; green: loss of Cyprus and battle of Lepanto; brown: war of Candia. The x axis is clipped to the years under study.", fig.height=4>>=
ggplot(marriages_by_year, aes(x=year,y=matrimonies))+geom_line()+
  geom_smooth() +
  geom_segment(x=1479, xend=1479,y=0,yend=80,color="red")+ # Black plague
  geom_segment(x=1510, xend=1510,y=0,yend=80,color="gold")+ # League of Cambrai
  geom_segment(x=1573, xend=1573,y=0,yend=80,color="green")+ # Loss of Cyprus and battle of Lepanto
  geom_segment(x=1645,xend=1645,y=0,yend=80, color="brown") + # Beginning of the Candia war
  ylim(0,80)+
  theme_minimal()+labs(y="Marriages")
@

To further validate the dataset, Figure \ref{fig:casenuove.marriages.validation} displays the annual number of recorder marriages together with a smoothed trend (blue line). It also marks four major shocks in the history of the Venetian republic \citep{lane1973venice}, indicated by colored vertical lines.\footnote{These events, their impact on the social network, and the corresponding regime changes in the Republic of Venice are analyzed in detail in \cite{histories4020012}}. The figure shows that after the Black Plague of 1478--79 (red line), and the War of the League of Cambrai (1508--1516) the number of marriages was almost always below the trend line (in blue). The loss of Cyprus  and battle of Lepanto of 1570--71 (green line)  go even further, designating a complete change of trend, that is accentuated by  the war of Candia (1645--1669)  which eventually led to the loss of Crete (brown line) and the Republic entering in a terminal decline phase. This, however, falls already outside the period we are interested in.


\subsection{Initial exploratory analysis}\label{ssec:exploration}

This section provides a first examination of the marriage network and its evolution over the period under study. This analysis rests on the assumption that, unlike patrilineal ties, marriage alliances created strong but comparatively transient connections. In particular, both \citet[p. 82]{finlay1980politicsrenaissance} and \citet[p. 143]{raines2013rameau} note that these ties typically lasted for about three generations, roughly spanning the period of co-residence across successive cohorts within the same household. On this basis, and assuming a generational length of approximately 25 years \citep{social:memory}, we analyze the network using a 75-year moving window: at any given time, we include only marital ties formed in the preceding 75 years, in order to capture the “living memory” of past social connections.

<<casenuove.graphs,echo=F,message=F,fig.cap="Marriage networks based on 75-year moving windows (50-year intervals). Gold nodes denote \\emph{longhi}, red nodes \\emph{grandi curti}, grey nodes other \\emph{curti}; dogal families are shown as squares.", out.width="50%", fig.show="hold", fig.height=6.15>>=
DEPTH_IN_YEARS <- 75
INITIAL_YEAR_OVERVIEW <- 1350
FINAL_YEAR_OVERVIEW <- 1550

window_sequence <- seq(from = INITIAL_YEAR_OVERVIEW, to = FINAL_YEAR_OVERVIEW, by = 50)
assortativity <- data.frame( curti_longhi = numeric(),
                             ducali = numeric(),
                             in_quaranta = numeric(),
                             distance_curti_longhi = numeric(),
                             distance_ducali_corti = numeric(),
                             distance_ducali_longhi = numeric(),
                             intra_longhi = numeric(),
                             intra_ducali = numeric(),
                             intra_corti = numeric(),
                             intra_quaranta = numeric(),
                             intra_non_quaranta = numeric(),
                             quaranta_e_non_quaranta = numeric(),
                             year = integer() )

graph_list <- vector("list",length(window_sequence))
excluded_families_list <- vector("list",length(window_sequence))
network_measures <- data.frame( dates = character(),
                                average_degree = numeric(),
                                average_clustering_coefficient = numeric(),
                                average_closeness = numeric() )
list_index <- 1

load("data/doges.years.rda")

for (y in window_sequence ) {

  last_year <- y + DEPTH_IN_YEARS

  marriages_window <- noble_marriages %>%
    filter(year <= last_year & year >= y)

  marriage_graph <- graph_from_data_frame(
    marriages_window,
    directed = FALSE,
    vertices = unique(c(marriages_window$husband_familyname_std, marriages_window$wife_familyname_std))
  )

  doges <- unique(doges.years[ doges.years$Start >= y & doges.years$Start <= y + DEPTH_IN_YEARS, ]$Family.doge)
  E(marriage_graph)$weight <- 1
  marriage_graph <- simplify(marriage_graph, edge.attr.comb = "sum")

  V(marriage_graph)$Faction <- ifelse(V(marriage_graph)$name %in% longhi, "Longhi", "Corti")
  V(marriage_graph)$types_curti_longhi <- ifelse(V(marriage_graph)$Faction == "Longhi", 1,2)
  assortativity_curti_longhi <- assortativity_nominal(marriage_graph, V(marriage_graph)$types_curti_longhi, directed = FALSE)

  V(marriage_graph)$Ducale <- ifelse(V(marriage_graph)$name %in% ducali, TRUE, FALSE)
  V(marriage_graph)$types_ducali <- ifelse(V(marriage_graph)$Ducale == TRUE, 1,2)
  assortativity_ducali <- assortativity_nominal(marriage_graph, V(marriage_graph)$types_ducali, directed = FALSE)

  V(marriage_graph)$InQuaranta <- ifelse(V(marriage_graph)$name %in% quaranta_famiglie, TRUE, FALSE)
  V(marriage_graph)$types_quaranta <- ifelse(V(marriage_graph)$InQuaranta == TRUE, 1,2)
  assortativity_quaranta <- assortativity_nominal(marriage_graph, V(marriage_graph)$types_quaranta, directed = FALSE)

  E(marriage_graph)$distances <- 1 / E(marriage_graph)$weight
  V(marriage_graph)$Group <- ifelse(V(marriage_graph)$name %in% longhi, "Longhi", ifelse(V(marriage_graph)$name %in% ducali, "Ducali", "Corti"))
  V(marriage_graph)$color <- ifelse(V(marriage_graph)$Group == "Longhi",
                                    "gold",
                                    ifelse(V(marriage_graph)$Group=="Ducali","red","darkgray"))

  V(marriage_graph)$shape <- ifelse(V(marriage_graph)$name %in% doges, "square", "circle")
  component <- components(marriage_graph)$membership
  marriage_graph_main <- subgraph(marriage_graph, V(marriage_graph)$name[component == 1])
  excluded_families_list[[list_index]] <- V(marriage_graph)$name[component != 1]

  par(mar = c(0, 0, 1, 0))                 # kill the default plot margins
  plot(marriage_graph_main,
        vertex.size = 5,
        vertex.label = NA,
        vertex.color = V(marriage_graph)$color,
        edge.width = E(marriage_graph)$weight,
        edge.color = adjustcolor("darkblue", alpha.f = 0.3),
        layout = layout_with_kk,
        main = paste("Marriage Network from", y, "to", last_year)
  )
  graph_list[[list_index]] <- marriage_graph
  list_index <- list_index+1

  network_measures <- rbind( network_measures,
                             data.frame( dates = paste(y, "-", last_year),
                                         average_degree = mean(degree(marriage_graph_main)),
                                         average_clustering_coefficient = mean(transitivity(marriage_graph_main)),
                                         average_closeness = mean(closeness(marriage_graph_main))
                                         )
                             )
}
@

Figure \ref{fig:casenuove.graphs}, which uses the Kamada-Kawai layout algorithm \citep{kamada1989algorithm} provides an overview of the evolution of the marital social network. It shows the main component of six networks constructed using the 75-year moving window, spaced at 50-year intervals (1350–1425, 1400–1475, etc.). In the graph, gold nodes represent \emph{longhi} families, red nodes \emph{ grandi curti} families  and grey nodes other \emph{curti} families. The \emph{ducali} families, i.e., families that had a doge elected in the period under consideration, are represented as squares. No families are excluded from the  main connected component of each 75-year network.
The figure highlights several important features of the network. Not every \emph{ducali} family occupies a central position in the network.
Moreover, the effects of the alleged \emph{curti} conspiracy are clearly visible: no gold squares appear in the second, third, and fourth graphs, i.e., between 1400 and 1575, since all doges were from  \emph{curti} families.

The graphs also reveal the remarkable stability of the three (overlapping) time windows at the center of the sequence, which exhibit very similar structural properties. By contrast, the first and the last windows depart from this pattern. Since the earliest window is affected by the lower coverage of the historical records, we focus on the transition from the fourth to the fifth window. Whereas  the network for 1500--1575 appears densely interwoven, with most families embedded in a compact core, the last networks (1550--1625) is looser, with a growing number of families outside the densely connected core.

Finally, there is little evidence of clear factionalization. In none of the periods do either the  \emph{grandi  curti} or the \emph{longhi} families form internally cohesive clusters that exclude the rest of the patriciate. Although peripheral positions are almost always occupied by smaller \emph{curti} families (grey nodes), neither the \emph{longhi} nor the \emph{grandi curti} consistently dominate the most central positions in the network, nor do they form distinct clusters separated from one another.

 <<casenuove.betweenness, echo=F,fig.cap="Betweenness centrality by rank across the five overlapping periods. Node colors are as in Figure~\\ref{fig:casenuove.graphs}; larger nodes denote \\emph{ducali} families.", out.width="50%", fig.show="hold", fig.height=5.75>>=
initial_year <- INITIAL_YEAR_OVERVIEW
for (graph in graph_list) {
  V(graph)$betweenness = betweenness(graph)
  betweenness_df <- data.frame( family= V(graph)$name, betweenness = V(graph)$betweenness,
                                color=V(graph)$color,
                                size=ifelse(V(graph)$shape == "square",4,2)
  )
  betweenness_df_sorted <- betweenness_df[order(betweenness_df$betweenness, decreasing=T),]
  betweenness_df_sorted <- betweenness_df_sorted[ betweenness_df_sorted$betweenness > 0,]
  betweenness_df_sorted$index <- seq_len(nrow(betweenness_df_sorted))
  print(ggplot( betweenness_df_sorted, aes(x=index,y=betweenness))+
          geom_point(color=betweenness_df_sorted$color,alpha=0.5,
                     size=betweenness_df_sorted$size)+
          scale_x_log10()+scale_y_log10(limits = c(0.1, 1900))+theme_minimal()+xlab(paste("Years", initial_year, "-", initial_year+DEPTH_IN_YEARS)))
  initial_year <- initial_year + 50
}
@

To better understand the structure of political intermediation within the Venetian patriciate, Figure \ref{fig:casenuove.betweenness} shows the distribution of betweenness centrality by rank across the five overlapping periods.  All graphs use the same log-log scale: the $y$-axis scale reports betweenness centrality, while the $x$ axis reports the rank of families with a betweenness value greater than zero. This common scaling makes it possible to compare the concentration of intermediation power across periods. Node colors follow the same coding as in Figure~\ref{fig:casenuove.graphs}: gold for \emph{longhi}, red for \emph{grandi curti}, and grey for other \emph{curti}. Larger points represent families that elected a doge during the corresponding period.

As the figure shows, no single family dominates the network in terms of betweenness centrality. Maximum betweenness values remain around 1000 with a slight decline observable in the 1500--1575 and 1550--1625 graphs. A further notable feature is that, rather than displaying the steep decay typically associated with a power-law distribution, all graphs exhibit a pronounced ``broken-stick'' pattern: a relatively large group of families shares similarly high betweenness values, followed by a sharp decline around the 100th rank. This pattern suggests the existence of a broad elite endowed with comparable intermediation power, rather than the dominance of few families. In turn, this supports the well-established interpretation of Venetian political institutions as mechanisms designed to prevent excessive concentration of power. At the same time, the sharp separation between highly central and peripheral families indicates that substantial inequalities persisted within the patriciate, despite the formal political equality of nobles. Peripheral families appear structurally dependent on a more central elite that mediated access to the wider network.

The distribution of colors across the graphs provides further insight into the composition of this elite. The forty families, i.e., the  \emph{longhi} and  \emph{grandi curti} families, rank higher in terms of centrality, whereas lower ranks are predominantly occupied by other \emph{curti} families. Nevertheless, no single faction consistently dominates the top positions across all periods. For example, in the third graph (1450--1525), the highest-ranked family does not belong to the forty families, while in the fourth graph all three colors appear among the most central families. Overall, the graphs point less to the stable predominance of a single faction than to a rotation of influence within a restricted elite.

 Turning to the \emph{ducali} families, represented by larger nodes, a further pattern emerges. Throughout most of the periods, the families that elected a doge are spread across the ranking and only rarely coincide with those occupying the very top positions in terms of betweenness. Several \emph{ducali} families are found well below the most central ranks. The  final period (1550--1625), which includes the years immediately following the end of the alleged conspiracy in 1612, is a modest exception, as as, in addition to lower-ranked \emph{ducali} families, the three most central families also succeeded in electing one of their members doge. These families were the \emph{grandi curti} Priuli and Donà (whose members Antonio Priuli and Nicolò Donà were elected in 1618) and the \emph{longhi} Bembo (Giovanni Bembo, elected in 1615), which was the second \emph{longhi} family elected to the dogeship after the end of the "conspiracy".
The fact that \emph{ducali} families are found throughout the ranking is consistent with an electoral system that required large majorities: winning the dogeship depended on building broad coalitions capable of attracting support from both central and peripheral segments of the patriciate.

This exploratory analysis suggests two main conclusions. First, the dogeship was only rarely secured by the family occupying the most central position in the marriage network. Second, the network provides little evidence of a persistent structural division between the alleged factions: ties between \emph{longhi} and \emph{curti} were widespread, and virtually all families belonged to a single connected component. These findings suggest that the long-lasting monopoly of the dogeship by the \emph{curti} cannot be explained solely in terms of betweenness centrality or the overall pattern of marriage ties. The following sections therefore explore whether other structural features of the network may account for it.

\section{Experiments and results}

<<casenuove.cohesiveness.sequence, echo=F>>=
INITIAL_YEAR_EXPERIMENTS <- 1400
FINAL_YEAR_EXPERIMENTS <- 1575

window_sequence <- seq(from = INITIAL_YEAR_EXPERIMENTS, to = FINAL_YEAR_EXPERIMENTS, by = 5)
@

We now turn to the evolution of the marriage network between \Sexpr{INITIAL_YEAR_EXPERIMENTS} and \Sexpr{FINAL_YEAR_EXPERIMENTS+DEPTH_IN_YEARS} with the aim of examining how its structure changed over the two centuries of the \emph{curti} monopoly and the years immediately following its end. To capture structural changes at a finer temporal resolution, we continue to use \Sexpr{DEPTH_IN_YEARS}-year moving windows but shift them every five years, rather than every fifty. This produces a sequence of \Sexpr{length(window_sequence)} overlapping networks, allowing us to follow the evolution of the network in considerably greater detail. The data for all network slices are available in the paper's online repository under a free license.


% What we are interested in is to check the cohesion of the different possible factions. Since we are speaking about a power core and a periphery, we are mainly speaking about distances in network terms, that is, how easy would be to reach any member of the social network from any other, and how these evolve; in time, a group can gain or lose cohesiveness if distances among them change, and it can also {\em dilute} itself among the rest if it is {\em closer} in network terms to its periphery. Our main hypothesis here would be that the faction that is able to {\em differentiate less} from its periphery while maintaining a high cohesion itself would be more likely to gather a qualified majority big enough to be able to get closer, or even achieve, election to office of dogeship.
We are interested in two main research questions; the first one is related to how could a small group of families, the {\em grandi curti}, manage to monopolize the highest office in Venice for more than two centuries. We will need to look at the network, and check if there are, for instance, clear-cut divisions that would mark real factional politics where the biggest divided sub-network obtains supremacy.

<<casenuove.cohesiveness.setup, echo=F, fig.height=5, fig.pos="h!tb", fig.cap="Evolution of the total number of families (red) and the number of families in the main connected component (black) (left panel), and the percentage of families belonging to the main connected component (right panel).", out.width="50%", fig.height=5, fig.show='hold'>>=

number_of_families_timeline <- data.frame( total_number = integer(),
                                           families_in_MCC = integer(),
                                           percentage_in_MCC = numeric(),
                                           year = integer())
previous_families <- NULL
family_changes <- list()
list_index <- 1
for (y in window_sequence ) {

  last_year <- y + DEPTH_IN_YEARS
  marriages_window <- noble_marriages %>%
    filter(year <= y + DEPTH_IN_YEARS & year >= y)

  marriage_graph <- graph_from_data_frame(
    marriages_window,
    directed = FALSE,
    vertices = unique(c(marriages_window$husband_familyname_std, marriages_window$wife_familyname_std))
  )

  # --- Track families added/removed vs. the previous window ---
  current_families <- V(marriage_graph)$name

  if (!is.null(previous_families)) {
    added   <- setdiff(current_families, previous_families)
    removed <- setdiff(previous_families, current_families)

    family_changes[[list_index]] <- list(
      year   = last_year,
      added       = added,
      removed     = removed,
      n_added     = length(added),
      n_removed   = length(removed)
    )
    list_index <- list_index+1
  }

  previous_families <- current_families
  # --- end tracking ---
  
  E(marriage_graph)$weight <- 1
  marriage_graph <- simplify(marriage_graph, edge.attr.comb = "sum")
  E(marriage_graph)$distances <- 1 / E(marriage_graph)$weight

  V(marriage_graph)$Group <- ifelse(V(marriage_graph)$name %in% longhi, "Longhi", ifelse(V(marriage_graph)$name %in% ducali, "Ducali", "Corti"))

  component <- components(marriage_graph)$membership
  marriage_graph_main <- subgraph(marriage_graph, V(marriage_graph)$name[component == 1])

  number_of_families <- length(V(marriage_graph)$name)
  families_in_MCC <- length(V(marriage_graph_main)$name)
  percentage_in_MCC <- families_in_MCC/number_of_families  * 100

  number_of_families_timeline <- rbind( number_of_families_timeline,
                                        data.frame( total_number = number_of_families,
                                                    families_in_MCC = families_in_MCC,
                                                    percentage_in_MCC = percentage_in_MCC,
                                                    year = last_year))

}

ggplot( number_of_families_timeline , aes(x=year, y=total_number) ) + geom_line( color="red") +
  geom_line(data=number_of_families_timeline, aes(y=families_in_MCC)) + theme_minimal()

ggplot( number_of_families_timeline, aes(x=year,y=percentage_in_MCC))+ geom_line()+ theme_minimal()
@


Figure~\ref{fig:casenuove.cohesiveness.setup} reports the size of the networks across the overlapping time windows. The left panel compares the total number of nodes (red line) with the number belonging to the main connected component (black line), while the right panel reports the percentage of families included in the main connected component. In both panels, the horizontal axis corresponds to the last year of each 75-year window.

The figure shows that, except for a few brief periods, the main connected component contains {\em all} families present in the time window. Thus, even if political divisions existed, they did not produce a fragmentation of the marriage network into separate components. Families that temporarily fell outside the main connected component remained few in number and were subsequently reabsorbed into it, rather than forming persistent alternative subnetworks.

Establishing that the network is connected is only the first step. We must also understand how closely families were connected to one another, as this provides insight into the mechanisms through which the \emph{grandi curti} were able to build the broad coalitions that sustained their political dominance. In an electoral system requiring the support of a large share of the patriciate, the ability of the \emph{grandi curti}—--or of their opponents—--to reach a substantial portion of the network was crucial. Having established that virtually all families belonged to a single connected component, the next question is how close the competing factions were to the rest of the network and, therefore, how easily they could mobilize support.


<<casenuove.analysis, echo=F, message=F, fig.cap="Evolution of intra-, extra-, and inter-faction average shortest path lengths (ASPL). Networks are computed over 75-year windows at 5-year intervals.", fig.height=5, fig.pos="h!tb">>=

noble_marriages_filtered <- read.csv("data/noble-marriages-year.csv", stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
# family_labels <- read.csv("data/family-labels-accession.csv", stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

longhi <- family_labels[ family_labels$Group == "Longhi", ]$Family
ducali <- family_labels[ family_labels$Ducale == 1,]$Family

curti_congiurati <- ducali[ !(ducali %in% c("Steno", "Ponte", "Cicogna")) ]

window_sequence <- seq(from = 1400, to = 1575, by = 5)
distances_window <- data.frame( total = numeric(),
                                congiurati = numeric(),
                                congiurati_norm = numeric(),
                                non_congiurati = numeric(),
                                non_congiurati_norm = numeric(),
                                congiurati_vs_non = numeric(),
                                congiurati_vs_non_norm = numeric(),
                                longhi = numeric(),
                                longhi_norm = numeric(),
                                non_longhi = numeric(),
                                non_longhi_norm = numeric(),
                                longhi_vs_non = numeric(),
                                longhi_vs_non_norm = numeric(),
                                longhi_vs_congiurati = numeric(),
                                longhi_vs_congiurati_norm = numeric(),
                                year = integer() )

core_periphery_timeline <- data.frame( clique_index_congiurati = numeric(),
                                       assortativity_congiurati = numeric(),
                                        clique_index_longhi = numeric(),
                                       assortativity_longhi = numeric(),
                                        assortativity_longhi_congiurati = numeric(),
                                        year = integer() )

number_of_marriages <- data.frame( year= integer(),
                                   intra_congiurati = numeric(),
                                   intra_longhi = numeric(),
                                   inter_congiurati_longhi = numeric(),
                                   extra_congiurati = numeric(),
                                   extra_longhi = numeric())

network_measures_year <- data.frame( year=integer(),
                                  closeness_congiurati = numeric(),
                                  closeness_longhi = numeric(),
                                  diameter = numeric(),
                                  clustering_coefficient=  numeric())

edges_year <- data.frame( year=integer(),
                          weight_average_global = numeric(),
                          weight_average_grandi_curti = numeric(),
                          weight_average_longhi = numeric() )

compute_gini <- function(x) {
  x <- na.omit(x)
  n <- length(x)

  if (n == 0) return(NA)
  if (sum(x) == 0) return(0)

  x <- sort(x)
  # Mathematical formula for Gini using ordered values
  G <- (2 * sum(seq_along(x) * x) / (n * sum(x))) - ((n + 1) / n)

  return(G)
}

# Average edge weight among a specific set of vertices (e.g., one faction)
avg_weight_within <- function(graph, vertex_names) {
  v <- V(graph)[V(graph)$name %in% vertex_names]
  edges_within <- E(graph)[v %--% v]
  mean(edges_within$weight)
}

transition_year <- data.frame( year= integer(),
                               global_transitivity = numeric(),
                               edge_density = numeric(),
                               average_constraint = numeric(),
                               gini_constraint = numeric(),
                               modularity = numeric(),
                               ratio = numeric()
)

for (y in window_sequence ) {

  last_year <- y + DEPTH_IN_YEARS
  marriages_window <- noble_marriages_filtered %>%
    filter(year <= last_year & year >= y)

  marriage_graph <- graph_from_data_frame(
    marriages_window,
    directed = FALSE,
    vertices = unique(c(marriages_window$husband_familyname_std, marriages_window$wife_familyname_std))
  )

  E(marriage_graph)$weight <- 1
  marriage_graph <- simplify(marriage_graph, edge.attr.comb = "sum")
  E(marriage_graph)$distances <- 1 / E(marriage_graph)$weight

  V(marriage_graph)$Group <- ifelse(V(marriage_graph)$name %in% longhi, "Longhi", ifelse(V(marriage_graph)$name %in% curti_congiurati, "Curti Congiurati", "Curti"))

  component <- components(marriage_graph)$membership
  marriage_graph_main <- subgraph(marriage_graph, V(marriage_graph)$name[component == 1])

  distance <- distances(marriage_graph_main, weights = E(marriage_graph_main)$distances)
  average_distance <- mean(distance)

  vertices_longhi <- V(marriage_graph_main)[V(marriage_graph_main)$Group == "Longhi"]
  vertices_non_longhi <- V(marriage_graph_main)[V(marriage_graph_main)$Group != "Longhi"]

  distance_longhi_non_longhi <- distances(marriage_graph_main, v = vertices_longhi, to = vertices_non_longhi, weights = E(marriage_graph_main)$distances)
  mean_longhi_non_longhi <- mean(distance_longhi_non_longhi)

  distances_longhi_longhi <- distances(marriage_graph_main, v = vertices_longhi, to = vertices_longhi, weights = E(marriage_graph_main)$distances)
  mean_longhi_longhi <- mean(distances_longhi_longhi)

  distances_non_longhi_non_longhi <- distances(marriage_graph_main, v = vertices_non_longhi, to = vertices_non_longhi, weights = E(marriage_graph_main)$distances)
  mean_non_longhi_non_longhi <- mean(distances_non_longhi_non_longhi)

  clique_index_longhi <- mean_longhi_non_longhi - mean_longhi_longhi

  vertices_congiurati <- V(marriage_graph_main)[V(marriage_graph_main)$Group == "Curti Congiurati"]
  vertices_non_congiurati <- V(marriage_graph_main)[V(marriage_graph_main)$Group != "Curti Congiurati"]

  distance_congiurati_non_congiurati <- distances(marriage_graph_main, v = vertices_congiurati, to = vertices_non_congiurati, weights = E(marriage_graph_main)$distances)
  mean_congiurati_non_congiurati <- mean(distance_congiurati_non_congiurati)

  distances_congiurati_congiurati <- distances(marriage_graph_main, v = vertices_congiurati, to = vertices_congiurati, weights = E(marriage_graph_main)$distances)
  mean_congiurati_congiurati <- mean(distances_congiurati_congiurati)

  distances_non_congiurati_non_congiurati <- distances(marriage_graph_main, v = vertices_non_congiurati, to = vertices_non_congiurati, weights = E(marriage_graph_main)$distances)
  mean_non_congiurati_non_congiurati <- mean(distances_non_congiurati_non_congiurati)

  distances_longhi_congiurati <- distances( marriage_graph_main, v = vertices_longhi, to = vertices_congiurati, weights = E(marriage_graph_main)$distances )
  mean_longhi_congiurati <- mean( distances_longhi_congiurati )

  clique_index_congiurati <- mean_congiurati_non_congiurati - mean_congiurati_congiurati

  number_of_marriages <- rbind( number_of_marriages,
                                data.frame( year=last_year,
                                            intra_congiurati = length(E(marriage_graph_main)[ vertices_congiurati %--% vertices_congiurati]),
                                            intra_longhi = length(E(marriage_graph_main)[ vertices_longhi %--% vertices_longhi]),
                                            inter_congiurati_longhi = length(E(marriage_graph_main)[ vertices_longhi %--% vertices_congiurati ]),
                                            extra_congiurati = length(E(marriage_graph_main)[ vertices_non_congiurati %--% vertices_congiurati ]),
                                            extra_longhi = length(E(marriage_graph_main)[ vertices_non_longhi %--% vertices_longhi ])
                                            )
  )

  distances_window <- rbind(distances_window,
                         data.frame( total = average_distance,
                                     congiurati = mean_congiurati_congiurati,
                                     congiurati_norm = mean_congiurati_congiurati / average_distance,
                                     non_congiurati = mean_non_congiurati_non_congiurati,
                                     non_congiurati_norm = mean_non_congiurati_non_congiurati / average_distance,
                                     congiurati_vs_non = mean_congiurati_non_congiurati,
                                     congiurati_vs_non_norm = mean_congiurati_non_congiurati / average_distance,
                                     longhi = mean_longhi_longhi,
                                     longhi_norm = mean_longhi_longhi / average_distance,
                                     non_longhi = mean_non_longhi_non_longhi,
                                     non_longhi_norm = mean_non_longhi_non_longhi / average_distance,
                                     longhi_vs_non = mean_longhi_non_longhi,
                                     longhi_vs_non_norm = mean_longhi_non_longhi / average_distance,
                                     longhi_vs_congiurati = mean_longhi_congiurati,
                                     longhi_vs_congiurati_norm = mean_longhi_congiurati/average_distance,
                                     year = last_year))

  V(marriage_graph)$types_congiurati <- ifelse(V(marriage_graph)$Group == "Curti Congiurati", 1,2)
  assortativity_congiurati <- assortativity_nominal(marriage_graph, V(marriage_graph)$types_congiurati, directed = FALSE)
  V(marriage_graph)$types_longhi <- ifelse(V(marriage_graph)$Group == "Longhi", 1,2)
  assortativity_longhi <- assortativity_nominal(marriage_graph, V(marriage_graph)$types_longhi, directed = FALSE)
  V(marriage_graph)$types_both <- ifelse(V(marriage_graph)$Group == "Longhi", 1, ifelse(V(marriage_graph)$Group == "Curti Congiurati",2,3))
  assortativity_longhi_congiurati <- assortativity_nominal(marriage_graph, V(marriage_graph)$types_both, directed = FALSE)

  core_periphery_timeline <- rbind(core_periphery_timeline,
                                     data.frame( clique_index_congiurati = clique_index_congiurati,
                                                 assortativity_congiurati = assortativity_congiurati,
                                                 clique_index_longhi = clique_index_longhi,
                                                 assortativity_longhi = assortativity_longhi,
                                                 assortativity_longhi_congiurati = assortativity_longhi_congiurati,
                                                 year = last_year ))

  # 1. Calculate closeness as a named vector
  closeness_scores <- closeness(marriage_graph_main, normalized=T)

  # 2. Match the scores to the names/rownames of your data frames
  closeness_congiurati <- mean(closeness_scores[vertices_congiurati$name], na.rm = TRUE)
  closeness_longhi     <- mean(closeness_scores[vertices_longhi$name], na.rm = TRUE)
  network_measures_year <- rbind( network_measures_year,
                             data.frame( year= last_year,
                                         closeness_congiurati= closeness_congiurati,
                                         closeness_longhi = closeness_longhi,
                                         diameter = diameter( marriage_graph_main),
                                         clustering_coefficient = transitivity(marriage_graph_main)
                                         )
                             )

  global_transitivity <- transitivity(marriage_graph_main, type="global")
  this_edge_density <- edge_density(marriage_graph_main)
  constraints <- constraint( marriage_graph_main)

  communities <- cluster_leiden(marriage_graph_main, resolution = 1)

  # 2. Compute Modularity Score (Q)
  modularity_score <- modularity(marriage_graph_main, membership(communities))

  transition_year <- rbind( transition_year,
                            data.frame( year= last_year,
                                        global_transitivity = global_transitivity,
                                        edge_density = this_edge_density,
                                        average_constraint = mean(constraints),
                                        gini_constraint = compute_gini( constraints),
                                        modularity = modularity_score,
                                        ratio = global_transitivity/this_edge_density)
  )
  
  edges_year <- rbind( edges_year,
                       data.frame( year= last_year,
                                   weight_average_global = mean(E(marriage_graph_main)$weight),
                                   weight_average_grandi_curti = avg_weight_within( marriage_graph_main, curti_congiurati),
                                   weight_average_longhi = avg_weight_within( marriage_graph_main, longhi)
                                   )
  )
}

