#                                 "Longhi" = "gold", "Longhi vs. Rest" = "gold",
#                                 "Longhi vs. Grandi Curti" = "goldenrod"
#                                 )) +
#   theme_minimal()

ggplot(distances_window, aes(x = year)) +
  geom_line(aes(y = congiurati, color = "Grandi Curti")) +
  geom_line(aes(y = congiurati_vs_non, color = "Grandi Curti vs. Rest"), linetype = "dotdash") +
  geom_line(aes(y = longhi, color = "Longhi")) +
  geom_line(aes(y = longhi_vs_non, color = "Longhi vs. Rest"), linetype = "dotdash") +
  geom_line(aes(y = longhi_vs_congiurati, color = "Longhi vs. Grandi Curti")) +
  labs(x = "Year",
       y = "Average Shortest Path Length") +
  scale_color_manual(
    name = "colour",
    breaks = c("Grandi Curti", "Grandi Curti vs. Rest",
               "Longhi", "Longhi vs. Grandi Curti", "Longhi vs. Rest"),
    values = c("Grandi Curti" = "red", "Grandi Curti vs. Rest" = "red",
               "Longhi" = "gold", "Longhi vs. Rest" = "gold",
               "Longhi vs. Grandi Curti" = "goldenrod"),
    guide = guide_legend(
      override.aes = list(
        linetype = c("solid", "dotdash", "solid", "solid", "dotdash")
      )
    )
  ) +
  theme_minimal()
@

We begin by measuring proximity using the average shortest path length (ASPL).  For each family, we first compute the average shortest path to a given set of nodes; we then average this quantity over all families belonging to the same faction. Figure~\ref{fig:casenuove.analysis} reports three measures:\begin{itemize}
 \item the intra-faction ASPL, computed as the average shortest path from each family to all other families within the same faction and then averaged over all families in the faction. As in the previous figures, red denotes the \emph{grandi curti} and gold the \emph{longhi},
 
 %Intra-faction, that is, average shortest path from one node in the faction to the rest; this is then averaged over all nodes. We use red for {\em grandi curti} and gold for {\em lunghi}, as usual
 \item the extra-faction ASPL, computed as the average shortest path from each family in a faction to all families outside that faction and then averaged over all families in the faction. These series are shown as dashed lines using the corresponding faction colors,
 
 %Extra-faction, that is, ASPL from faction nodes to the rest of the network. Please note that this includes the nodes in the other faction. We use dashed lines with the faction colors.
 \item the inter-faction ASPL, computed as the average shortest path over all pairs of \emph{longhi} and \emph{grandi curti} families. This series is shown in orange, combining the red and gold used for the two factions.
 %Inter-faction, ASPL from {\em lunghi} to {\em grandi curti} nodes. We use orange, mixing red and gold, for this line
 \end{itemize}
Distances are computed using weighted edges: when two families are connected by two marriages, the corresponding edge has length 0.5 rather than 1. This explains why, for example, the intra-faction ASPL ranges between approximately 0.4 and 0.6. 

As can be seen from Figure~\ref{fig:casenuove.analysis}, the \emph{longhi} remain more closely connected to one another than the \emph{grandi curti} throughout most of the period, the only exception being two brief intervals around 1520 and 1570, when the two lines cross. Two additional crossings deserve attention. Shortly after 1600, the intra-faction ASPL of the \emph{grandi curti} becomes larger than the inter-faction ASPL. The difference is slight, but it implies that members of the \emph{grandi curti} are, on average, closer to the \emph{longhi} than to other \emph{grandi curti}.
 A second crossing occurs in the extra-faction (dashed) lines: around 1575, the \emph{grandi curti} become more distant from the rest of the network than the \emph{longhi}, and this gap widens after 1600. Both transitions take place against a general increase in shortest-path lengths from the late sixteenth century onward, indicating that families became progressively more distant from one another as the network expanded.

 %QUI DA CAMBIARE FINO A CLOSENESS CENTRALITY 844

This chart thus helps answer the two research questions. From the beginning of the period under study up until the end of the 1500, the {\em grandi curti} had a slight distance advantage to the rest of the network (which we should remind includes the {\em longhi}); this distance kept decreasing more or less at the same pace as the {\em longhi} with the rest of the network. This decreasing average distance implied that it was relatively easy for them to create the grand coalitions needed to win the elections, as it happened. At the same time, by the end of the 1500 and beginning of the 1600, the data reveal several shifts happening concurrently:\begin{itemize}
\item ASPL starts to increase: the network is expanding, with the position of these two factions not keeping pace with that expansion.
\item Almost simultaneously, the ASPL from the {\em longhi} to the rest of the network surpasses the one between the {\em grandi curti} and the rest of the network, indicating structural changes where the position of the {\em longhi} has improved with respect to the {\em grandi curti}.
\item A few years later, inter-faction ASPL start to be lower than intra-{\em grandi curti} distance, indicating a greater integration between the two factions than how {\em grandi curti} relate to each other. This indicates that collective action of {\em grandi curti} and {\em longhi} together becomes easier than for the {\em grandi curti} by themselves; but again it is an indication of deep structural changes in the structure of the network.
\end{itemize}

As a complementary measure we compute the normalized average closeness centrality of each faction \citep{freeman1979,wasserman1994}. Unlike the intra- and extra-faction ASPL, which separately capture proximity within the faction and to the rest of the network, closeness centrality captures how close each family is to the network as a whole by taking into account its shortest-path distances to all other reachable families. Averaging this quantity over all families provides a single measure of the proximity of the faction to the network as a whole.

<<casenuove.closeness, warning=FALSE, echo=F, message=F, fig.cap="Evolution of closeness centrality over time.", fig.height=3, fig.pos="h!tb">>=
ggplot( network_measures_year, aes(x = year)) +
  geom_line(aes(y = closeness_congiurati, color = "Grandi Curti")) +
  geom_line(aes(y = closeness_longhi, color = "Longhi")) +
  labs(x = "Year",
       y = "Average closeness per group") +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("Grandi Curti" = "red", "Longhi" = "gold")) +
  theme_minimal()

# Check correlation
# Split at the crossover (~1550, based on your chart)
post_crossover <- network_measures_year %>% filter(year >= 1550)

# 1. Raw correlation on levels (can be inflated by shared trend)
cor_levels <- cor.test(post_crossover$closeness_congiurati, post_crossover$closeness_longhi)

# 2. Correlation on year-over-year changes (removes shared trend, tests real co-movement)
post_crossover <- post_crossover %>%
  arrange(year) %>%
  mutate(
    delta_congiurati = closeness_congiurati - lag(closeness_congiurati),
    delta_longhi      = closeness_longhi - lag(closeness_longhi)
  )

cor_deltas_post <- cor.test(post_crossover$delta_congiurati, post_crossover$delta_longhi)


# 3. For comparison: same two tests on the pre-crossover period
pre_crossover <- network_measures_year %>% filter(year < 1550)
cor_levels_pre <- cor.test(pre_crossover$closeness_congiurati, pre_crossover$closeness_longhi)

pre_crossover <- pre_crossover %>%
  arrange(year) %>%
  mutate(
    delta_congiurati = closeness_congiurati - lag(closeness_congiurati),
    delta_longhi      = closeness_longhi - lag(closeness_longhi)
  )

cor_deltas_pre <- cor.test(pre_crossover$delta_congiurati, pre_crossover$delta_longhi)
@

Figure~\ref{fig:casenuove.closeness} reports the average closeness centrality of the two dominant factions, the \emph{grandi curti} (red line) and the \emph{longhi} (gold line). Values remain relatively high throughout the period. An average closeness of about 0.5 implies that, on average, any family could reach another family in approximately two steps within the main connected component, which includes almost all families at every point in time (Figure~\ref{fig:casenuove.cohesiveness.setup}).

The figure again reveals a marked change around the middle of the sixteenth century. Until approximately 1550, the \emph{grandi curti} exhibit consistently higher closeness centrality than the \emph{longhi}. This advantage disappears in 1550, after a sharp decline in the closeness of the \emph{grandi curti}. From that point onward, closeness increases for both factions, with the \emph{longhi} maintaining a slight advantage until the two series converge towards the end of the period.

These results provide further evidence for our first research question. During the period in which they dominated Venetian politics, the \emph{grandi curti} occupied more central positions in the marriage network, allowing them to reach the rest of the patriciate through shorter paths. After the mid-sixteenth century, however, this advantage largely disappeared.

Another interesting pattern emerges after the crossover. The evolution of closeness centrality becomes much more synchronized across the two factions. The correlation between changes in the two series rises from \Sexpr{round(cor_deltas_pre$estimate,2)} before the crossover to \Sexpr{round(cor_deltas_post$estimate,2)} afterwards, with the corresponding p-values equal to \Sexpr{round(cor_deltas_pre$p.value,3)} and \Sexpr{round(cor_deltas_post$p.value,3)}, respectively.
 This stronger correlation, coupled with the better significance, suggests a structural change in the network, with the two factions evolving in a more coordinated manner over time.

<<casenuove.closeness.histo, echo=F, message=F, fig.cap="Evolution of closeness centrality over time", fig.height=5, fig.pos="h!tb">>=
years_of_interest <- c(1500, 1575, 1625)

closeness_snapshots <- data.frame(
  family = character(),
  closeness = numeric(),
  Faction = character(),
  year = integer()
)

for (last_year in years_of_interest) {
  y <- last_year - DEPTH_IN_YEARS

  marriages_window <- noble_marriages_filtered %>%
    filter(year <= last_year & year >= y)

  marriage_graph <- graph_from_data_frame(
    marriages_window,
    directed = FALSE,
    vertices = unique(c(marriages_window$husband_familyname_std, marriages_window$wife_familyname_std))
  )

  E(marriage_graph)$weight <- 1
  marriage_graph <- simplify(marriage_graph, edge.attr.comb = "sum")

  V(marriage_graph)$Group <- ifelse(V(marriage_graph)$name %in% longhi, "Longhi",
                              ifelse(V(marriage_graph)$name %in% curti_congiurati, "Grandi Curti", "Curti"))

  component <- components(marriage_graph)$membership
  main_id <- which.max(table(component))
  marriage_graph_main <- induced_subgraph(marriage_graph, which(component == main_id))

  closeness_scores <- closeness(marriage_graph_main, normalized = TRUE)

  closeness_snapshots <- rbind(closeness_snapshots, data.frame(
    family = V(marriage_graph_main)$name,
    closeness = closeness_scores,
    Faction = V(marriage_graph_main)$Group,
    year = last_year
  ))
}

# Keep only the two factions being compared
closeness_snapshots <- closeness_snapshots %>%
  filter(Faction %in% c("Grandi Curti", "Longhi"))

group_means <- closeness_snapshots %>%
  group_by(year, Faction) %>%
  summarise(mean_closeness = mean(closeness), .groups = "drop")

ggplot(closeness_snapshots, aes(x = closeness, fill = Faction, color = Faction)) +
  geom_density(alpha = 0.4, linewidth = 0.8) +
  geom_rug(aes(color = Faction), sides = "b", linewidth = 0.6, alpha = 0.7, show.legend = FALSE) +
  geom_vline(data = group_means, aes(xintercept = mean_closeness, color = Faction),
             linetype = "dashed", linewidth = 0.8, show.legend = FALSE) +
  facet_wrap(~ year, ncol = 1) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("Grandi Curti" = "red", "Longhi" = "gold")) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("Grandi Curti" = "red", "Longhi" = "gold")) +
  labs(x = "Closeness centrality", y = "Density",
       title = "Distribution of closeness centrality by faction") +
  theme_minimal()
@

Averages, however, can only give you a general idea of what is happening; since we have a variety of agents for every faction, checking the distribution would give us a better idea of how close are nodes belonging to each faction to the rest of the network. We have chosen three dates: \Sexpr{paste(years_of_interest, collapse=", ")}, and made a density plot with the distribution of closeness centrality for each faction; this is represented in Figure \ref{fig:casenuove.closeness.histo}. What we see is that when the {\em grandi curti} have the lead, in 1500, they are more or less centrally distributed, with a peak centered around the average. However, the situation changes in \Sexpr{years_of_interest[2]}, with several "bumps" that indicate that, even if on average {\em lunghi} are closer to the rest of the network, there is a sizable group of {\em grandi curti} that have a very high closeness; still, there is yet another group of {\em lunghi} that have the highest closeness in the network. This indicates that closeness-related {\em challenges} will not have a fixed outcome, and that probably other factors need to be taken into account. In the final chart, in 1625, averages are close together but again distribution is so complex that it is likely that closeness no longer plays a role. 

Looking again at the research questions, the fact that the distribution of closeness is better for the {\em grandi curti}, at least until the middle of the XVI, can explain why they kept the office of the doge {\em until the time their collective closeness was on average worse than that for the lunghi}. However, even after that date the small difference and the fact that there were families with a very low closeness meant that in a closure-dominated network they could still manage to create the grand coalitions needed to obtain the doge for them.

What emerges from the analysis so far is that, until the middle of the sixteenth century, the \emph{grandi curti} possessed an effective mechanism for building broad political coalitions. Their central position in the marriage network enabled them to leverage social ties to coordinate support for their preferred candidates. Around the mid-sixteenth century, however, this pattern began to change. This marked the beginning of the transition that would eventually end the \emph{grandi curti}'s long-standing monopoly over the dogeship. Looking at Figure~\ref{fig:casenuove.cohesiveness.setup}, we see that this synchronization and {\em sorpasso} occur when the number of families in the network reaches its peak; the number of families included in networks slices from that moment is continuously shrinking, at least until mid-XVII when it increases again, after a brief bump (a single family) in the first quarter of the century. A shrinking {\em marriage pool} can effectively have that effect: with less nodes, normalized closeness effectively increases; this has a quantifiable effect on the structure, but it might not be the only one; we will need to look at how it affects the global network structure in some other way.


<<casenuove.constraint, echo=F, fig.cap="Global evolution of the network in two structure-related aspects: average constraint and edge density", fig.height=3, fig.pos="h!tb">>=
ggplot( transition_year, aes(x=year))+ geom_line( aes(y=global_transitivity, color="global_transitivity")) + geom_line( aes(y=edge_density, color="edge_density"))+geom_line( aes(y=average_constraint, color="average constraint")) + theme_minimal() + labs(y="Structural variable values")
min_constraint_year <- transition_year[which(transition_year$average_constraint == min(transition_year$average_constraint)),]$year
max_density_year <- transition_year[which(transition_year$edge_density == max(transition_year$edge_density)),]$year
@

Figure \ref{fig:casenuove.constraint} shows the evolution of several structural variables along time: average constraingt (red), edge density (green) and global transitivity (blue). They are represented in the same scale since its values are in a similar range. The first impression is that despite its dramatic effect on some node-level measures, these three variables do not seem to be affected in any particular way by the peak number of vertices reached in the network slice that ends in 1550. All seem to have smaller changes in trend a bit later, however, that might be interesting to study.

The line marked "constraint" shows the value of Burt's constraint \citep{burt1992structural}. This measures how constrained, on average, is a vertex to reach the rest of the network, and is computed from the density of its ego network. From 1550, it continues a downward trend that reaches a peak for in \Sexpr{min_constraint_year}. More than a structural change, what the graph from 1550 to \Sexpr{min_constraint_year} is the fact that peripheral nodes, with a degree equal to 1 and thus a high constraint, are being pruned from the network. This is certainly a structural change, however it is more a transition to a change of regime that a change of regime per se. 

The change in Burt's constraint is the mirror image of the evolution of the edge density, that is, how many edges are there over all possible ones: it increases essentialy from the beginning of the period up until \Sexpr{max_density_year}, when it starts to decline.

%However, the perception and the cohesion seems to unravel towards the end of the period, which might explain the return to the {\em longhi} as preferred families for dogeship. And they draw a relatively complicated scenario, with dynamic factions that are at the same time well related to each other through the common political and commercial (including matrimonial) framework of the Republic of Venice, but keeping their relatively separate identities using the same set of links. As is shown in Figure \ref{fig:casenuove.cohesiveness.setup}, there is a substantial demographic shift by mid-XVII century which is right behind the end of the {\em ducale} doge era, thus it cannot explain the shift (although it might have contributed to its permanency).

%We are more interested on the trend in the first quarter of the XVII century, when effectively the {\em longhi} retrieved their access to the dogate. Figure \ref{fig:casenuove.analysis.normalized} possibly shows the clearest picture. This chart shows normalized average shortest past distances. Intra-faction distances reflect cohesiveness within a faction, and what we see is that while {\em longhi} and {\em grandi curti} were very close together in terms of normalized distance until the end of the XVI century, the difference between them starts to increase by the beginning of the XVII. Same happens with the distance between the factions and the rest of the network: while {\em grandi curti} maintain a slight advantage over the {\em longhi}, eventually the latter begin being being closer to the {\em periphery} by the end of that century. It is interesting also, in this chart, to check the distances between the two "factions", {\em longhi} and {\em grandi curti}. While during most of the period distances between them are longer than intra-faction distances, there come a point at the beginning of the 17th century, before the change of regime, when {\em grandi curti} are on average further away from each other (solid blue line) than from the {\em longhi} (green line).

<<casenuove.assortativity, echo=F, message=F, fig.cap="Evolution of assortativity for different type combinations: grandi curti vs. non, longhi vs. non, and longhi vs. curti",  fig.pos="h!tb", fig.height=5>>=
ggplot( core_periphery_timeline, aes(x = year)) +
  geom_line(aes(y = assortativity_congiurati, color = "Grandi Curti")) +
  geom_line(aes(y = assortativity_longhi, color = "Longhi")) +
  geom_line(aes(y = assortativity_longhi_congiurati, color = "Longhi vs. congiurati")) +
  labs(x = "Year",
       y = "Assortativity") +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("Grandi Curti" = "red", "Longhi" = "gold", "Longhi vs. congiurati" ="green")) +
  theme_minimal()
@

We can also measure how every faction interacted with the rest of the nobles using assortativity \cite{newman2003mixing}, that is, how they link within the group and across faction boundaries; in this case we work with {\em name} assortativity. The evolution of within-group and inter-group assortativity is shown in Figure \ref{fig:casenuove.assortativity}. It is interesting to note how the two factions have different marriage {\em policies}, and they diverge in the first half of the XV: while {\em longhi} drop their assortativity marrying {\em outside} their group, the {\em grandi curti} go in the opposite direction: they preferably marry other families within the group. But more interesting is to follow inter-group assortativity, that is, how the 16 families that form the {\em grandi curti} faction marry the {\em longhi} and vice-versa: from the moment mentioned above they split, it follows the assortativity coefficient of the {\em longhi}, that is, they preferably marry with each other; taking into account that the {\em grandi curti} did not, what this implies is that the amount of marriages where the {\em longhi} participated was higher than the ones where there were members of the opposite faction. But more interesting is the moment these two lines decouple by the beginning of the XVII: while the {\em longhi} still keep marrying preferably {\em outside} their group, they {\em do not} marry with {\em grandi curti} preferably, keeping the inter-group assortativity or slighly positive.

<<casenuove.number_of_marriages, echo=F, message=F, fig.cap="Evolution of the number of marriages within, inter and extra groups", fig.height=5, fig.pos="h!tb">>=
ggplot( number_of_marriages, aes(x = year)) +
  geom_line(aes(y = intra_congiurati, color = "Grandi Curti")) +
  geom_line(aes(y = intra_longhi, color = "Longhi")) +
  geom_line(aes(y = extra_congiurati, color = "extra congiurati")) +
  geom_line(aes(y = extra_longhi, color = "extra longhi")) +
  geom_line(aes(y = inter_congiurati_longhi, color = "Longhi vs. congiurati")) +
  labs(title = "Number of marriages over time",
       subtitle = "Intra, inter and extra groups",
       x = "Year",
       y = "Number of marriages") +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("Grandi Curti" = "red", "Longhi" = "gold", "Longhi vs. congiurati" ="green",
                                "extra congiurati" = "light blue", "extra longhi" ="darkgoldenrod2")) +
  theme_minimal()

@

What we show in Figure \ref{fig:casenuove.number_of_marriages} is the total number of marriages for every 75-year graph. The  inter-group  number of marriages starts initially with a low value, but eventually it overtakes either number of marriages, following more or less the same trend as both intra-group marriages. Extra-group marriages reach a peak by the end of the XVI, and since then extra-group marriages fall faster than either intra- or inter-group marriages. Seen this way, the change of regime that stopped the {\em grandi curti} from continuing holding the office of doge seems, in part, demographic: when the number of marriages fell together with the population of nobles, the {\em longhi}, being more numerous and having a more extensive network of first-degree alliances, could leverage better their position, partly keeping the {\em grandi curti} out of the doge's office. As a matter of fact, the first {\em longhi} family that managed to become doge was the Contarini, one of the more numerous families within the Venetian noble class. As a matter of fact, they returned to office yet again in 1630 with Nicolò Contarini.

%
<<casenuove.diameter, echo=F, message=F, fig.cap="Evolution of the clustering coefficient over time. The green line marks the year when Francesco Contarini was elected.", fig.height=3, fig.pos="h!tb">>=
ggplot( network_measures_year, aes(x = year, y = clustering_coefficient)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_point( aes(size=diameter))+
  geom_segment(x=1623, xend=1623,y=0.20,yend=0.45,color="green")+ # Francesco Contarini elected doge
  labs(title = "Clustering coefficient over time",
       x = "Year",
       y = "Diameter") +
  theme_minimal()
@
%
This is provoked by a drastic change in the structure of the network; Figure \ref{fig:casenuove.diameter} plots the transitivity, that is, the clustering coefficient, which loses half its value in a century, and 1/8th its value in less than 20 years. This effectively creates a shock on the network, removing nodes and edges and creating structural holes. The diameter of the network, represented by point size, also experiments changes and tends to increment, implying that the collective coalition-forming power of the {\em grandi curti} no longer can be leveraged. This provokes a change of regime: from collective closeness-based coalition formation, to individual bargaining power based on brokerage which, again, leads to the return to power of family with the highest betweenness, the Contarini.

\section{Conclusions and discussion}

